===Etymology===
{{borrowing|fr}} {{term|meringue|lang=fr}}, from {{etyl|dum|en}} {{term|meringue||light evening meal|lang=dum}}, derivative of {{etyl|dum|en}} *{{term||meren|to dip or soak bread|lang=dum}}, from {{etyl|odt|en}} *{{term||meren|lang=odt}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*marjaną||to grind, pound}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*mer-||to rub, pack}}. Cognate with {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|meringe|lang=gml}} (from {{term|mern||to dip bread in wine|lang=gml}}), {{etyl|gmh|-}} {{term|merunge|lang=gmh}} (from {{term|mëren||to soak bread in wine or water for dinner|lang=gmh}}), {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|merian||to purify, cleanse, test|lang=ang}}.

Alternate etymology derives {{etyl|odt|en}} *{{term||meren|lang=odt}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*marhin||soup of bread and wine or water}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*mark-}}, {{term/t|ine-pro|*merk-||wet}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# A mixture consisting of beaten egg whites and sugar which is added to the tops of pies then browned.
#: ''The key to a good [[baked Alaska]] is the '''meringue''' topping.''
# A shell made of this mixture which serves as the receptacle for fruit, ice cream or sherbet.
#: ''Shirley likes to have strawberry with her '''meringue'''.''

